# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcoholic-beverage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] One drink per hour is approximately the amount the body can metabolize.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Three drinks per night was selected as a target below the amounts recognized by NIAAA as binge drinking (4 drinks for women, 5 drinks per men).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] In both national research and at FE Warren rates of injuries, assaults, criminal behavior and other problems increase dramatically with binge drinking.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] The first tier included screening of all personnel for binge drinking utilizing a measure such as the Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Persons identified as possibly at risk were offered an alcohol screening consultation with the Alcohol and Drug Abuse Prevention and Treatment (ADAPT) program.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Consistent with Air Force policy all active duty members who had alcohol-related misconduct incidents were also referred for evaluation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Based on evaluation results individuals were provided educational and motivational enhancement interventions, or if found to have a substance use disorder, entered into a treatment program.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] This included development of the name 0-0-1-3 as both a slogan and a guideline for low risk alcohol use.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Personnel from the age range at highest risk for binge drinking, 18-25, were involved in development and execution of these actions.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Metrics collected in 2005 showed a "74% decrease in alcohol-related incidents such as driving violations, public drunkenness, domestic violence, sexual assault, thefts, and other infractions.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] The base also reported 81% fewer cases of underage drinking and 45% fewer drunken-driving arrests." Multiple other military bases adopted elements of the program including a grant-funded trials at five bases.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] The program served as the model for the Air Force's Culture of Responsible Choices (CoRC) program.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] A **0-0-1-3** program was also implemented by the senior administration of the United States Naval Academy in response to a string of alcohol-related incidents that generated a large amount of negative publicity during the 2005-2006 school year.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Its primary aim there is to "promote responsible alcohol use" within the brigade of midshipmen.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] While the senior leadership at the Naval Academy insists that 0-0-1-3 is only a guideline for responsible alcohol use, its enforcement involves mandatory, random breathalyzer tests for all midshipmen regardless of age or rank.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Those found in "violation" of 0-0-1-3 (evidenced by having a BAC above 0.08) are placed on record as having alcohol abuse issues, and repeat offenders are subject to severe administrative infractions, up to and including expulsion.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Military Academy (West Point) nor the U.S.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/0-0-1-3] Air Force Academy conducts random breathalyzers or punishes students simply for blowing above a particular BAC when not driving a motor vehicle.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/10-12-p01] This list contains selected positive numbers in increasing order of magnitude, including counts of things, dimensionless quantities, and probabilities.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/10-12-p01] Each number is given a name in the short scale, which is used in English-speaking countries, as well as a name in the long scale, which is used in some of the countries that do not have English as their national language.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/10-12-p01] (100000; one hundred thousand or a lakh).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1919-norwegian-prohibition-referendum] A **referendum on introducing prohibition** was held in Norway on 5 and 6 October 1919.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1919-norwegian-prohibition-referendum] Partial prohibition had been in effect since 1917, and the prohibition proposal did not include all types of alcohol, only spirits.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1919-norwegian-prohibition-referendum] The proposal was approved by 61.6% of voters.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1919-norwegian-prohibition-referendum] A second referendum on whether the prohibition should be maintained was held in 1926, resulting in an overturning of the law.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1926-norwegian-continued-prohibition-referendum] A consultative and facultative **referendum on continuing with prohibition** was held in Norway on 18 October 1926.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1926-norwegian-continued-prohibition-referendum] Partial prohibition had been effective since 1917, and following a 1919 referendum, spirits and dessert wine had also been banned.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1926-norwegian-continued-prohibition-referendum] Partially caused by pressure from France, which saw its exports of alcoholic beverages fall, a referendum was organised to decide whether prohibition should be continued.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1926-norwegian-continued-prohibition-referendum] Popular support for prohibition fell in all counties.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1926-norwegian-continued-prohibition-referendum] It was overwhelmingly rejected in and around Oslo, as well as in other urban areas like Bergen.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/1926-norwegian-continued-prohibition-referendum] As a result, the law was abolished and prohibition brought to an end.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/20th-century-cocktail] The **20th century** is a cocktail created in 1937 by a British bartender named C.A.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/20th-century-cocktail] Tuck, and named in honor of the celebrated *20th Century Limited* train which ran between New York City and Chicago from 1902 until 1967.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/20th-century-cocktail] The recipe was first published in 1937 in the *Café Royal Cocktail Book* by William J Tarling, President of the United Kingdom Bartenders' Guild and head bartender at the Café Royal.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/20th-century-cocktail] Shake in an iced cocktail shaker, and strain into a cocktail glass.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Isoamyl alcohol is an ingredient in the production of banana oil, an ester found in nature and also produced as a flavouring in industry.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] It is a common fusel alcohol, produced as a major by-product of ethanol fermentation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Isoamyl alcohol is one of the components of the aroma of *Tuber melanosporum*, the black truffle.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Fusel alcohols like isoamyl alcohol are fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of isoamyl are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] The compound has also been identified as a chemical in the pheromone used by hornets to attract other members of the hive to attack.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Isoamyl alcohol can be separated from fusel oil by either of two methods: shaking with strong brine solution and separating the oily layer from the brine layer; distilling it and collecting the fraction that boils between 125 and 140 °C.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Further purification is possible with this procedure: shaking the product with hot limewater, separating the oily layer, drying the product with calcium chloride, and distilling it, collecting the fraction boiling between 128 and 132 °C.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Isoamyl alcohol can be synthesized by condensation of isobutene and formaldehyde which produces isoprenol, then hydrogenation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] It is a colourless liquid of density 0.8247 g/cm3 (0 °C), boiling at 131.6 °C, slightly soluble in water, and easily dissolved in organic solvents.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] It has a characteristic strong smell and a sharp burning taste.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] On passing the vapour through a red-hot tube, it decomposes into acetylene, ethylene, propylene, and other compounds.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] It is oxidized by chromic acid to isovaleraldehyde, and it forms addition compounds crystals with calcium chloride and tin(IV) chloride.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Besides its use in the synthesis of banana oil, isoamyl alcohol is also an ingredient of Kovac's reagent, used for the bacterial diagnostic indole test.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] It is also used as an antifoaming agent in the chloroform isoamyl alcohol reagent.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/3-methyl-1-butanol] Isoamyl alcohol is used in a phenol–chloroform extraction mixed with the chloroform to further inhibit RNase activity and prevent solubility of RNAs with long tracts of poly-adenine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] A **Seven and Seven** or **7 and 7** is a highball cocktail, a mixed alcoholic drink containing Seagram's Seven Crown, which is a blended whiskey, and 7 Up, which is a lemon-lime soft drink.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] It was one of the most popular drinks in the United States during the 1970s.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] In the 1977 film *Saturday Night Fever*, Tony Manero (John Travolta) orders a 7 and 7 while at the bar of a strip club.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] In the pilot episode of The O.C., Ryan Atwood orders a 7 and 7 cocktail at a party but only takes a sip before Kirsten Cohen takes it away from him.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] In "Mixology Certification" the 10th episode of season 2 of the series *Community*, when celebrating his 21st birthday, Troy Barnes (Donald Glover) orders a 7 and 7, which he says was his late uncle's favorite drink.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] In the 2018 film *BlacKkKlansman*, Laura Harrier as Patrice Dumas orders a 7 and 7 in the bar scene after the Kwame Ture speech.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/7-and-7] Namesake of the song "7 & 7" from the 2003 album *Diamonds & Gasoline* by the Turnpike Troubadours and mentioned in the first verse.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:alcoholic-beverage/alcoholic-beverage] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
